      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study performed; discretization error quantified as <5% change in all QoIs between penultimate and final mesh refinement levels.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm construct model. Three mesh densities were evaluated; QoI change between the two finest meshes was <2% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm. Richardson extrapolation confirms discretization error is negligible relative to experimental uncertainty. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence tolerances documented and set to values at least one order of magnitude below the acceptance threshold for QoI differences.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver residual tolerances were set to 1×10⁻⁶ for force and displacement norms across all ensemble codes. Sensitivity checks confirmed QoI insensitivity to tighter tolerances. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments conducted by analyst not involved in original model construction.",
      "rationale": "An independent senior analyst reviewed all model inputs, boundary condition definitions, contact formulations, and material assignments for each ensemble member prior to final simulation runs. Discrepancies identified during review were corrected and documented. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Nonlinear elastic-plastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening used for titanium alloy components; contact mechanics formulated with penalty method; geometric nonlinearity enabled for large-displacement bending response.",
      "rationale": "The FEA model employs a bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model calibrated against Ti-6Al-4V coupon test data. Geometric nonlinearity (NLGEOM) is activated to capture the large-displacement bending response characteristic of the F1717 test. Frictional contact between screw and vertebral body block surrogate is modeled with a penalty formulation. Model form is appropriate for the COU physics. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, ultimate strength, hardening slope) sourced from lot-specific coupon testing of the same material heat used for the pedicle screw constructs; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of test articles.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (880 MPa), and tangent modulus (1.8 GPa) were measured from Ti-6Al-4V coupons machined from the same bar stock as the test screws. Screw geometry was verified by coordinate measuring machine (CMM) against nominal CAD. UHMWPE block geometry and material properties sourced from supplier data sheets with independent verification. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs tested; samples drawn from production lot; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to nominal geometry within manufacturing tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories. All constructs were drawn from a single production lot and dimensionally inspected. Coefficient of variation in experimental QoIs was <8%, indicating acceptable sample consistency. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Testing performed under at least two distinct loading rates or fixture configurations to characterize sensitivity of QoIs to test condition variability.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717-compliant loading condition (displacement-controlled, 5 mm/min crosshead speed) at both laboratories. No variation in loading rate or fixture configuration was explored. This limits confidence in the generalizability of the validation comparison. Achieved level (1) is below required level (2); this is the one identified gap in the credibility assessment. Risk is partially mitigated by the consistency of results across two independent laboratories and the conservatism of the acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to test article and test setup conditions; any deviations documented and sensitivity-analyzed.",
      "rationale": "Direct mapping between FEA inputs and measured test article properties was verified. Boundary condition equivalency was confirmed by comparing fixture stiffness in FEA against measured crosshead compliance. Minor deviation in UHMWPE block density was sensitivity-analyzed and found to produce <1% change in QoIs. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval computed for each QoI; E/uval <1.96 required; percent difference <10% required for all three QoIs across all ensemble members.",
      "rationale": "E/uval was computed as (FEA prediction − experimental mean) / combined uncertainty (model + experimental). Values were 0.84 (stiffness), 1.12 (yield force), and 0.97 (force at 40 mm) across the ensemble average. All values <1.96. Percent differences ranged from 1.2% to 7.8%, all within the 10% acceptance bound. Required level met for all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly linked to the clinical failure modes of interest (screw fatigue, construct loosening) and are the same metrics used in the regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in the regulatory submission and directly correspond to the biomechanical failure modes assessed in the COU. These metrics are standard endpoints in ASTM F1717 and are accepted by FDA as surrogates for in vivo construct performance under physiological bending loads. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending bench test) is the same scenario as the COU; no extrapolation beyond the validated domain is required for the intended regulatory use.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is the ASTM F1717 static compression-bending test, which is identical to the COU scenario. The FEA model is applied within the validated loading regime and geometry. No domain extrapolation is required. The multi-laboratory, multi-code ensemble design provides additional confidence in the representativeness of the validation evidence. Required level met."
    }
